5. docker network create equifox-net
   creates a custom Docker network named equifox-net. Assigns it a private subnet (e.g. 172.18.0.0/16). Sets up internal DNS. Allows containers to communicate with each 
   other by container name. It provides easier service discovery, and is preferred over the default bridge network for production‑like setups. Isolated from other 
   Docker networks unless connected explicitly. 
   Why create a custom Docker network?
     Custom networks are better than the default bridge network because they provide:
     ✅ Automatic DNS-based container name resolution
     ✅ Better isolation
     ✅ Cleaner microservice architecture
     ✅ Easier container-to-container communication

   to verify the network run:                         docker network ls.
   to Inspect details run/Verify the connection:      docker network inspect equifox-net
   to Start a container on the network:               docker run -d --name app1 --network equifox-net nginx
                                                      docker run -d --name app2 --network equifox-net busybox sleep 1000
   app2 can ping app1 using container name:           docker exec -it app2 ping app1
   Container name = hostname. No need to know IP addresses. This does NOT work reliably on the default bridge network
   Connecting existing containers:                    docker network connect equifox-net container_name
   to disconnect containers:                          docker network disconnect equifox-net container_name

   
   Common real‑world use case:
     Example: Microservices 
              frontend  → backend  → database
              
              docker network create equifox-net
              docker run --network equifox-net --name backend backend-image
              docker run --network equifox-net --name frontend frontend-image

              Frontend can call backend as: http://backend:8080

   Optional: Creating with custom subnet. Useful when integrating with external systems. Avoiding IP conflicts
         docker network create --subnet 192.168.100.0/24 equifox-net

6. Docker Compose Networking: Docker Compose automatically creates and manages networks for multi‑container applications, so containers can discover and
   communicate with each other by service name.  
   1️⃣ Default Networking in Docker Compose:         docker compose up
      You run the command "docker compose up" from a terminal/command prompt on your machine, in the directory that contains the Docker Compose file. If the file name 
      is not docker-compose.yml, specify it explicitly:   docker compose -f fileName.yml up
      Docker Compose automatically does the following:
      ✅ Creates a default bridge network
      ✅ Attaches all services to that network
      ✅ Enables DNS-based service name resolution

      Example: Default Network
      docker-compose.yml
        version: "3.9"
        services:
          web:
           image: nginx
          api:
           image: node

     Docker Compose creates a network named: <project_name>_default
     web can reach api using: http://api
     api can reach web using: http://web
     Service name = hostname
     ❌ IP addresses should never be hardcoded
     ✅ Use service names instead

  2️⃣ Custom Networks in Docker Compose
     Custom Bridge Network Example
     version: "3.9"

services:
  frontend:
    image: nginx
    networks:
      - app-net

  backend:
    image: node
    networks:
      - app-net

networks:
  app-net:
    driver: bridge


✅ Both services communicate via app-net
✅ Fully isolated from other Compose projects

3️⃣ Multiple Networks (Advanced but Common)
    Used when: Some services must be public
               Others must stay private
    ✅ Frontend + Backend + Database Example
version: "3.9"

services:
  frontend:
    image: nginx
    networks:
      - public-net

  backend:
    image: node
    networks:
      - public-net
      - private-net

  db:
    image: mysql
    networks:
      - private-net

networks:
  public-net:
  private-net:


🔐 Result

frontend ↔ backend ✅
backend ↔ db ✅
frontend ❌ db (isolated)

4️⃣ External Networks (Using Existing Docker Networks)
   Use when: Network already exists
             Multiple Compose projects must communicate

   Example
    1. First, create the network:     docker network create equifox-net
    2. Then reference it in Compose:
version: "3.9"

services:
  app:
    image: nginx
    networks:
      - equifox-net

networks:
  equifox-net:
    external: true

✅ Docker Compose will not recreate it
✅ Ideal for shared infrastructure (API, Auth, Gateway)

5️⃣ Exposing Ports vs Networking (Important Clarification)
   🔁 Internal communication (container ↔ container)
       Service name → internal port
       backend:
          ports:
            - "8080:8080"

      ports is NOT needed for internal networking.

   🌍 External access (host ↔ container)
      ✅ Only needed to access services from your machine
       ports:
         - "8080:8080"


