7. docker network connect equifox-net pg16.  what does this command do
   connects an already running container named pg16 to the Docker network equifox-net allowing it to communicate with other containers on that network using Docker’s 
   internal DNS without restarting the container. Docker allows a container to belong to multiple networks.
   So after this command: pg16 may still be on its original network AND also on equifox-net. This is called multi‑network attachment.
     ✅ Container pg16 becomes part of the equifox-net network
     ✅ pg16 gets:
       A new IP address on equifox-net
       A network interface on that network
       DNS visibility to other containers on equifox-net
     ✅ pg16 can:
        Communicate with other containers on equifox-net
        Be accessed by container name (pg16)

8. Difference between docker run --network equifox-net pg16  and  docker network connect equifox-net pg16
   docker run --network equifox-net  creates a container and attaches to equifox-net network , while docker network connect equifox-net pg16 attaches an already running
   container to equifox-net network without restarting it. The latter is especially useful for multi‑network setups and live fixes.
   When to use docker network connect
    ✅ Add a database to an app network
    ✅ Attach a debug container
    ✅ Connect legacy containers
    ✅ Temporary production fixes
    ✅ Multi‑tier networking designs

9. explain   docker compose -f docker-compose.optionB.fixed.yml up --build
   is used to build and start a multi‑container application defined in a specific Docker Compose file. 
   1️⃣ docker compose
     Invokes Docker Compose (v2), which is built into Docker CLI
     Used to manage multi‑container applications
    🔹 Note: This is the modern replacement for docker-compose

   2️⃣ -f docker-compose.optionB.fixed.yml
      Specifies a custom Compose file
      Overrides the default file name (docker-compose.yml)
      ✅ This allows you to:
          Maintain multiple configurations (OptionA, OptionB, prod, dev, fixed, etc.)
          Choose which setup to run at execution time
          example:
                 docker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml up
                 docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml up

   3️⃣ up
      Creates networks, volumes, and containers
      Starts all defined services
      Attaches logs to the terminal (unless -d is used)
    Equivalent steps:
        Create network(s)
        Create container(s)
        Start container(s)
        Stream logs to stdout

   4️⃣ --build
       Forces Docker to rebuild images before starting containers. Only images defined via Dockerfile are rebuilt. Services using image: (like postgres:16) are not rebuilt
       Even if images already exist
       ✅ This is useful when:
          Dockerfile was modified
          Application code changed
          Dependencies changed
          You want to ensure the latest build is used

Stop and remove everything:         docker compose -f docker-compose.optionB.fixed.yml down
Rebuild without cache:              docker compose -f docker-compose.optionB.fixed.yml build --no-cache        then run 
Start services (foreground)         docker compose -f docker-compose.optionB.fixed.yml up
Start services (background)         docker compose -f docker-compose.optionB.fixed.yml up -d
Run a single service:               docker compose -f docker-compose.optionB.fixed.yml up app

10. Difference between
    docker compose up -> builds and starts all services and creates everything needed.
    docker compose run -> executes a one‑off command in a new temporary container.
    docker compose start -> starts only existing stopped containers without rebuilding or recreating them.
    
11. difference between
    docker compose stop -> halts running containers without removing them.
    docker compose down -> stops and removes containers and networks.

12. docker exec -it pg16 psql -U postgres  
    This command opens an interactive PostgreSQL (psql) session inside a running Docker container named pg16, logging in as the postgres user.
    Especially useful when PostgreSQL is not exposed via ports or you want direct container access.
    ✅ docker exec
       Executes a command inside a running container
       The container must already be up and running
    ✅ -it :  -it allows you to type commands interactively, like a real shell.
    ✅ pg16
        Name (or ID) of the Docker container
        Typically refers to a PostgreSQL 16 container
    ✅ psql
        PostgreSQL’s command‑line client
        Used to run SQL commands, manage databases, inspect schemas, etc.
    ✅ -U postgres
        Specifies the database user
        postgres is the default superuser in PostgreSQL

  🔹 Common Variations
    ✅ Connect to a specific database:    docker exec -it pg16 psql -U postgres mydb
    ✅ Open a shell first, then run psql:  docker exec -it pg16 bash
                                            psql -U postgres

  🔹 Important Notes
     ❌ Container must be running
     ❌ psql must be installed inside the container (it is by default in Postgres images)
     ✅ Authentication works because the command runs inside the container

